Vice President Kamala Harris and Secretary of Transportation Pete Buttigieg held a meeting to discuss disability rights and the progress that has been made since the passage of the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) 33 years ago. They acknowledged the challenges that people with disabilities still face, such as voting rights, access to reproductive healthcare, and barriers to small business ownership. They also discussed the impact of AI algorithms on people with disabilities and the need for accessible transportation, particularly in air travel. The Vice President emphasized the importance of an accessible America and thanked the attendees for their leadership. Former Representative Tony Coelho, a long-time advocate for disability rights, also spoke at the meeting and praised the current administration's support for the disability community. The meeting concluded with Harris expressing gratitude to the attendees and the start of the official discussion.